{"id":"2004.12476","submitter":"Karim Benakli","authors":"Karim Benakli, Carlo Branchina and Ga\\\"etan Lafforgue-Marmet","title":"Revisiting the Scalar Weak Gravity Conjecture","comments":"21 pages, 1 figure. References and few comments added","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1140/epjc/s10052-020-8268-0","report-no":null,"categories":"hep-th hep-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We revisit the Scalar Weak Gravity Conjecture and investigate the possibility\nto impose that scalar interactions dominate over gravitational ones. More\nprecisely, we look for consequences of assuming that, for leading scalar\ninteractions, the corresponding gravitational contribution is sub-dominant in\nthe non-relativistic limit. For a single massive scalar particle, this leads us\nto compare four-point self-interactions in different type of potentials. For\naxion-like particles, we retrieve the result of the Axion Weak Gravity\nConjecture: the decay constant $f$ is bounded by the Planck mass, $f <\n{M_{Pl}}$. Similar bounds are obtained for exponential potentials. For quartic,\npower law and Starobinsky potentials, we exclude large trans-Planckian field\nexcursions. We then discuss the case of moduli that determine the scalars\nmasses. We retrieve the exponential dependence as requested by the Swampland\nDistance Conjecture. We also find extremal state masses with field dependence\nthat reproduces both the Kaluza-Klein and winding modes behaviour. In\nparticular cases, our constraints can be put in the form of the Refined de\nSitter Conjecture.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 26 Apr 2020 20:41:53 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 11 May 2020 16:32:16 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-02-03"}
